5 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
6 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
7 Article – Education
8 9.5–404.
9 (a) The State Board shall adopt rules and regulations for licensing and operating
10 child care centers.
11 (b) These rules and regulations shall:
12 (1) Ensure safe and sanitary conditions in child care centers;
13 (2) Ensure proper care, protection, and supervision of children in child care
14 centers;
15 (3) Ensure the health of children in child care centers by:
16 (i) Monitoring children for signs and symptoms of child abuse;
17 (ii) Instructing licensees and staff concerning child abuse detection
18 and reporting;
19 (iii) Monitoring health practices to help prevent the spread of disease;
20 (iv) Monitoring the care of infants and children with special needs;
21 and
22 (v) Prohibiting the administration of corporal punishment to
23 discipline a child;
24 (4) Promote the sound growth and development of children in child care
25 centers;
26 (5) Promote proper nutrition and developmentally appropriate practices
27 by:
28 (i) Establishing training and policies promoting breast–feeding;
29 (ii) 1. Requiring compliance with the United States Department
30 of Agriculture Child and Adult Care Food Program standards for beverages served to

SENATE BILL 252 3
1 children, except that milk that is not nonfat or low fat may be ordered by a health care
2 practitioner or requested by a parent or guardian; and
3 2. Prohibiting beverages other than infant formula that
4 contain added sweetener or caffeine; and
5 (iii) Setting limits on screen time;
6 (6) Carry out otherwise the purposes and requirements of this subtitle,
7 including imposition of intermediate sanctions to ensure compliance;
8 (7) Prohibit a child from remaining at a child care center for more than 14
9 hours in 1 day unless the Department issues an exception for that child based on guidelines
10 set by the State Superintendent;
11 (8) [(i)] Require that a child care center have in attendance at all times
12 at least 1 individual who is responsible for supervision of children, including children on
13 field trips, and who holds a current certificate indicating successful completion of approved:
14 [1.] (I) Basic first aid training through the American Red Cross
15 or through a program with equivalent standards; and
16 [2.] (II) Cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training through
17 the American Heart Association or through a program with equivalent standards
18 appropriate for the ages of children for whom care is provided in the child care center; [and
19 (ii) Require that a child care center serving more than 20 children
20 have in attendance certificate holders described in item (i) of this item in a ratio of at least
21 1 certificate holder for every 20 children CERTIFICATE HOLDERS TO CHILDREN SET BY
22 THE DEPARTMENT;]
23 (9) Require that the minimum age of a child care teacher in a child care
24 center be at least 18 years old and an individual may not be precluded from being a child
25 care teacher solely for being 18 years old;
26 (10) (i) Require that a child care center that receives notice of a
27 contaminated drinking water supply from the child care center’s supplier of water, in
28 accordance with § 9–410 of the Environment Article or otherwise, send notice of the
29 drinking water contamination to the parent or legal guardian of each child attending the
30 child care center; and
31 (ii) Require that the notice sent by the child care center shall:
32 1. Be sent within 10 business days after receipt of the notice
33 of contamination from the child care center’s water supplier;

4 SENATE BILL 252
1 2. Be in writing;
2 3. Identify the contaminants and their levels in the center’s
3 water supply; and
4 4. Describe the child care center’s plan for dealing with the
5 water contamination problem until the child care center’s water is determined by the
6 appropriate authority to be safe for consumption;
7 (11) (i) Require a child care center to have a written emergency
8 preparedness plan for emergency situations that require evacuation, sheltering in place, or
9 other protection of children, such as in the event of fire, natural disaster, or other
10 threatening situation that may pose a health or safety hazard to the children in the child
11 care center;
12 (ii) Require the plan under item (i) of this item to include:
13 1. A designated relocation site and evacuation route;
14 2. Procedures for notifying parents or other adults
15 responsible for the child of the relocation;
16 3. Procedures to address the needs of individual children,
17 including children with special needs;
18 4. Procedures for the reassignment of staff duties during an
19 emergency, as appropriate; and
20 5. Procedures for communicating with local emergency
21 management officials or other appropriate State or local authorities; and
22 (iii) Require a child care center to train staff and ensure that staff are
23 familiar with the plan;
24 (12) Require a child care center to have window coverings in accordance with
25 § 5–505 of the Family Law Article; and
26 (13) Subject to subsection (c) of this section, establish probationary
27 employment qualifications for an individual who is applying for the first time to be a child
28 care teacher in a child care center in the State that serves preschool or school–age children
29 who are at least 3 years old.
30 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
31 1, 2025.

